His will , made in 1631 , was prefaced by ‘ so full and so open a protestation against the hierarchy and the ceremonies , that the prelatical party would not suffer it to be put among the records of the court when the will was tendred to be proved ’ ( Clark , in Life of
Julines Herring
) . On 21 Feb. 1634 a copy of the introduction to the will of ‘ Humphrey Fen the eldest ’ was received by Archbishop Laud from the bishop of Coventry and Lichfield . This preamble ( only ) was printed as ‘ The Last Will and Testament with the Profession of Faith of Humphrey Fenn , ’ &c . , 1641 , sm . 8vo ( no place of printing ) .
